00:08:24.079 --> 00:08:26.000
So first, version control.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:27.040
What is it?

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:31.040
So it's a practice of tracking and managing changes to software code.

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:33.840
Now, I don't know everyone's background.

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.760
It sounds like most folks are data scientists,

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:38.719
but if you're like me, the idea of version control

00:08:38.719 --> 00:08:40.080
and you're just getting started was like,

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:43.359
oh, that's for the hard-hitting software engineers,

00:08:43.359 --> 00:08:45.119
people doing really powerful stuff,

00:08:45.119 --> 00:08:47.119
way beyond the practice of a data scientist.

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:48.640
That's not the case.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:52.080
Version control is super important for data scientists as well.

00:08:53.039 --> 00:08:54.479
And we're going to talk all about it today.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:56.719
And to use version control,

00:08:56.719 --> 00:09:01.039
you typically have to use a version control system or a VCS.

00:09:01.039 --> 00:09:04.400
And Git tends to be the most popular VCS out there.

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:06.640
There's other ones you may have heard of like SVN,

00:09:07.359 --> 00:09:08.880
but really, Git is the most popular.

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:13.280
And you use Git to manage an evolution of a set of files.

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:16.159
So your R scripts, your Shiny apps, your Plumber APIs,

00:09:16.159 --> 00:09:18.159
your R Markdown, your core code documents,

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:20.400
all of your source code altogether.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:22.799
You track that, and all of those files together

00:09:22.799 --> 00:09:24.559
is known as a repository.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:27.679
And so you can take your repository,

00:09:27.679 --> 00:09:29.679
and if you want, you can host it

00:09:29.679 --> 00:09:32.080
on a repository hosting service.

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:34.559
That sounds like most folks are leveraging GitHub today,

00:09:34.559 --> 00:09:37.280
but there's a variety of options for you to choose from,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.119
many of which use Git, such as Bitbucket and GitLab.

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:42.799
There's also SourceForge,

00:09:42.799 --> 00:09:45.679
but really anywhere else you can host a repository

00:09:45.679 --> 00:09:47.679
and track changes of these source files,

00:09:48.239 --> 00:09:50.719
that can serve as your repository hosting service.

00:09:52.799 --> 00:09:54.799
Now, how do you actually use Git?

00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:57.599
Git is actually a piece of software.

00:09:57.599 --> 00:10:00.159
So I would say most computers nowadays

00:10:00.159 --> 00:10:03.200
have Git pre-installed on it when you buy the computer.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.119
But if you don't, you will actually have to

00:10:05.119 --> 00:10:06.559
physically install it,

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:09.280
just like you would install the open source RStudio IDE.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:10.479
It's a piece of software.

00:10:11.359 --> 00:10:14.239
And it's typically, when it was first designed,

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:15.119
and even to this day,

00:10:15.119 --> 00:10:17.520
it's most commonly leveraged

00:10:17.520 --> 00:10:20.400
from within the terminal or command line.

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:21.919
And again, if you're like me,

00:10:21.919 --> 00:10:24.400
a data scientist that really didn't have much,

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:26.000
you know, computer science background

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.599
coming into data science,

00:10:27.599 --> 00:10:30.239
the idea of using Git from the terminal like this

00:10:30.239 --> 00:10:33.840
or like the command line was extremely daunting.

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:35.760
And I was like, I'm not going to bother learning this.

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:37.440
But because of that,

00:10:38.719 --> 00:10:41.039
most popular IDEs today,

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:43.440
including the RStudio IDE,

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:47.599
has some type of integrated support for version control.

