00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:17.199
So what is an RStudio Project?

00:17:17.199 --> 00:17:20.719
Again, this is going to be a directory on your computer,

00:17:20.719 --> 00:17:22.880
either your local computer or somewhere on your server

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:24.719
if you're using Posit Workbench, for example.

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:27.599
And within this working directory,

00:17:28.479 --> 00:17:30.079
all of your code lives, right?

00:17:30.079 --> 00:17:32.959
So your R scripts, your R Markdown documents,

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:34.880
your Shiny apps, all of your source code.

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.280
It also includes all of your data,

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:38.959
your results, your tables, your figures.

00:17:39.599 --> 00:17:40.880
And also it's optional,

00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:43.439
but you can have all the packages associated

00:17:43.439 --> 00:17:45.040
with this project actually

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:46.880
within the working directory itself.

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:50.319
Really the take-home message with RStudio Projects

00:17:50.319 --> 00:17:52.160
is that it isolates your project.

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:54.000
So you can work on one project

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
and not worry about it impacting

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.520
some other project on your system,

00:17:57.520 --> 00:17:58.880
which could be a huge nightmare.

