That's probably the most intuitive way.

00:23:49.119 --> 00:23:50.400
There's also a button for this.

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:51.839
So, right here underneath the edit,

00:23:51.839 --> 00:23:54.400
you'll see this little kind of opaque box

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:55.280
with the R inside of it

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:56.719
and a little plus icon.

00:23:56.719 --> 00:23:58.239
That's another way to create a project.

00:23:58.239 --> 00:23:59.359
So, that will do the same thing.

00:24:00.160 --> 00:24:01.359
But for me personally,

00:24:01.359 --> 00:24:02.719
I actually like to work over here

00:24:02.719 --> 00:24:04.239
in the top right hand corner

00:24:04.239 --> 00:24:05.199
of my screen.

00:24:05.199 --> 00:24:07.839
You'll see currently it says project none.

00:24:07.839 --> 00:24:09.520
That's another great indicator

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:10.959
to let you know that you're not

00:24:10.959 --> 00:24:11.920
within a project.

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:14.000
So, let's go ahead and change that.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:15.199
I'm going to click on this box

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:17.920
and we'll select new project.

00:24:19.359 --> 00:24:20.479
And once we do that,

00:24:20.479 --> 00:24:22.079
we'll get a pop-up menu here.

00:24:22.079 --> 00:24:23.119
That same pop-up menu

00:24:23.119 --> 00:24:24.160
I was showing you before.

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:25.760
We can create a brand new project

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:27.199
in a new directory,

00:24:27.199 --> 00:24:28.880
an existing directory,

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:30.880
or we can pull in a project

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:32.160
from version control.

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:33.680
And that's what we're going to do today.

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:34.560
So, let me go ahead and click

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:35.199
on this option.

00:24:36.079 --> 00:24:36.880
It's going to ask

00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:38.319
which version control system

00:24:38.319 --> 00:24:39.119
do you want to use?

00:24:39.119 --> 00:24:40.239
And before this demo,

00:24:40.239 --> 00:24:41.359
we are using Git,

00:24:41.359 --> 00:24:43.119
but we do also support subversion.

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:44.479
So, I'll select Git.

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:46.880
And now we need to provide

00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:49.040
the repository URL.

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:49.920
So, let me switch back

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:51.760
to my GitHub repository.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:52.479
I'm going to select

00:24:52.479 --> 00:24:53.680
this green code button

00:24:53.680 --> 00:24:54.719
and I'm going to copy

00:24:55.280 --> 00:24:57.280
the URL for my repository.

00:24:58.800 --> 00:24:59.839
I'm back into RStudio

00:24:59.839 --> 00:25:01.040
and I'm going to paste it in.

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:02.719
And I'll hit tab.

00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:04.479
It's going to auto-populate

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:06.160
what it thinks the repository name is.

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:07.680
I'll just leave it as test repo.

00:25:08.479 --> 00:25:09.520
And then you want to place

00:25:09.520 --> 00:25:10.319
this directory,

00:25:10.319 --> 00:25:11.439
this RStudio project,

00:25:11.439 --> 00:25:12.800
in whatever location you want.

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:14.239
I'm just going to go ahead

00:25:14.239 --> 00:25:16.000
and place it inside of this directory

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:17.119
called posit projects

00:25:17.119 --> 00:25:18.239
that I created previously.

00:25:19.199 --> 00:25:20.560
And that's pretty much it.

00:25:20.560 --> 00:25:21.839
We'll hit create project.

00:25:22.959 --> 00:25:24.319
It's going to pull in

00:25:24.319 --> 00:25:25.359
that readme file

00:25:25.359 --> 00:25:27.760
from the GitHub repository.

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:28.959
And anytime you create

00:25:28.959 --> 00:25:30.000
an RStudio project,

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.359
it's always going to open up

00:25:31.359 --> 00:25:32.880
a new RStudio session.

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:33.520
So, we'll just give this

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:34.719
a few seconds to boot up.

00:25:40.560 --> 00:25:40.959
All right.

00:25:41.599 --> 00:25:42.239
So, here we are

00:25:42.239 --> 00:25:44.319
within a fresh RStudio session.

00:25:44.319 --> 00:25:45.439
We still have our console

00:25:45.439 --> 00:25:46.239
over here in the top

00:25:46.239 --> 00:25:47.199
on the left-hand side.

00:25:48.079 --> 00:25:49.680
You'll see in the file directory,

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:51.119
we have a few new files.

00:25:51.119 --> 00:25:51.839
So, we have this thing

00:25:51.839 --> 00:25:52.959
called a gitignore.

00:25:52.959 --> 00:25:53.599
We're not going to talk

00:25:53.599 --> 00:25:54.880
too much about it today,

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:56.319
but just know that RStudio

00:25:56.319 --> 00:25:57.520
added this file for me.

00:25:58.239 --> 00:25:59.119
And then you're also going to see

00:25:59.119 --> 00:26:00.640
this rproj file.

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:02.560
Every time you create a project,

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:04.079
this rproj file will be

00:26:04.079 --> 00:26:05.439
in that working directory.

00:26:05.439 --> 00:26:07.040
So, kind of the topmost directory

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:08.319
of your project.

00:26:08.319 --> 00:26:09.680
And you can always go back

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:11.040
to that top level directory

00:26:11.040 --> 00:26:13.119
by clicking this little box icon

00:26:13.119 --> 00:26:13.920
in the top right.

00:26:14.479 --> 00:26:15.680
This is kind of a cool feature

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:16.560
that I only learned

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:17.439
about like a year ago.

00:26:17.439 --> 00:26:18.400
So, I always like to kind of

00:26:18.400 --> 00:26:18.959
show it off.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:20.319
All right.

00:26:21.199 --> 00:26:22.239
Now, two important things

00:26:22.239 --> 00:26:23.119
to note currently.

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:25.359
Here in the very top,

00:26:25.359 --> 00:26:27.040
you're going to see test repo.

00:26:27.040 --> 00:26:28.160
So, if you're within

00:26:28.160 --> 00:26:29.520
an RStudio project,

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:30.640
you should see the name

00:26:30.640 --> 00:26:31.760
of your project in the top.

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:32.160
That's going to be

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:33.359
another great indicator

00:26:33.359 --> 00:26:34.800
to let you know you're within

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:35.839
an RStudio project.

00:26:36.719 --> 00:26:37.760
And now, if you look

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:38.880
at your environment tab,

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:40.000
so this quadrant up here

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.119
in the top right,

00:26:41.119 --> 00:26:42.079
we scroll over,

00:26:42.079 --> 00:26:43.760
you'll now see this Git tab

00:26:43.760 --> 00:26:44.560
right here.

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:44.880
All right.

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:45.760
And this is going to be

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:46.959
that Git integration

00:26:46.959 --> 00:26:48.160
we're going to focus on today.

00:26:48.800 --> 00:26:50.000
And currently we're seeing

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.760
two files in this directory.

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:53.119
This .gitignore

00:26:53.119 --> 00:26:54.880
and this rproj file.

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:57.199
So, again, these were two new files

00:26:57.199 --> 00:26:59.040
that RStudio added for me.

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:00.319
So, currently they're not

00:27:00.319 --> 00:27:02.079
being tracked by version control,

00:27:02.079 --> 00:27:02.880
which is represented

00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:03.920
by these question marks.

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:05.920
Basically, Git sees these files

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:06.560
and it's like,

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:07.280
do I track these?

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:08.160
Do I not track these?

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:09.280
I don't know what to do with them.

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:10.000
Hence why you're going

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:11.040
to see those question marks.

00:27:12.079 --> 00:27:12.640
All right.

00:27:12.640 --> 00:27:13.599
But for right now,

00:27:13.599 --> 00:27:14.560
that's going to be our focus.

00:27:15.359 --> 00:27:17.119
So, we've gone back to our slides.

00:27:17.839 --> 00:27:19.520
We've created that GitHub repository

00:27:20.079 --> 00:27:20.959
and we've pulled it

00:27:20.959 --> 00:27:22.239
in as an RStudio project.

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:24.000
So, let's go ahead and step

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
through a few additional

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:27.199
kind of features you can do

00:27:27.199 --> 00:27:28.239
with the RStudio IDE

00:27:28.239 --> 00:27:29.520
and the Git integration.

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:30.319
And then we'll actually do

00:27:30.319 --> 00:27:31.760
some more data science-y stuff.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:34.800
So, the next thing I want to demonstrate

00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:36.640
is how to create a branch.

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:38.000
Now, we're not going to focus

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:39.199
a lot today on like,

00:27:39.199 --> 00:27:40.640
you know, when to create a branch,

00:27:40.640 --> 00:27:42.160
why you want to create a branch.

00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:44.479
Just know that it is an important tool

00:27:44.479 --> 00:27:45.520
with version control.

00:27:46.319 --> 00:27:47.680
Let me just actually go to the slides here

00:27:47.680 --> 00:27:48.719
and kind of talk a little bit

00:27:48.719 --> 00:27:49.680
more about branches.

00:27:50.800 --> 00:27:52.640
So, what exactly are branches?

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:55.119
Well, they allow you to take a detour

00:27:55.119 --> 00:27:56.959
from the mainstream of development

00:27:56.959 --> 00:27:58.239
and do work without changing

00:27:58.239 --> 00:27:59.040
that mainstream.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:00.239
So, if you look at this diagram

00:28:00.239 --> 00:28:01.599
in the top right,

00:28:01.599 --> 00:28:03.439
think of these like black dots

00:28:03.439 --> 00:28:05.599
as like your main development.

00:28:05.599 --> 00:28:06.239
So, maybe you're working

00:28:06.239 --> 00:28:07.439
on a Shiny application

00:28:07.439 --> 00:28:09.040
and this is your production version

00:28:09.040 --> 00:28:10.160
of your Shiny application.

00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:12.160
Typically, you don't want to make

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:13.439
any changes directly

00:28:13.439 --> 00:28:16.160
to that polished production application.

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:16.959
And what would be nice

00:28:16.959 --> 00:28:18.319
is if you can just kind of branch

00:28:18.319 --> 00:28:19.439
off to the side,

00:28:19.439 --> 00:28:20.719
try out some new features

00:28:20.719 --> 00:28:22.239
and hey, if it works out great,

00:28:22.239 --> 00:28:23.520
eventually you can merge it

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:24.640
back into that mainstream.

00:28:25.280 --> 00:28:26.479
So, this is why branches

00:28:26.479 --> 00:28:27.760
are super important.

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:29.040
So, we're just going to show you

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:32.160
in this demo how to create a branch

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:33.439
using the RStudio IDE.

00:28:34.319 --> 00:28:37.839
So, let me come back to the RStudio IDE.

00:28:38.479 --> 00:28:40.560
If we look over here in the Git tab,

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:42.000
we have this additional toolbar

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:43.040
and we're going to spend some time

00:28:43.040 --> 00:28:45.199
talking about all these various buttons.

00:28:45.199 --> 00:28:46.560
But to start, you're going to see

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:48.000
over here on the right hand side,

00:28:48.560 --> 00:28:51.280
this little pink kind of blocky button,

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:53.520
this is the way to create a new branch.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:55.199
And right next to it,

00:28:55.199 --> 00:28:56.400
it's going to let you know

00:28:56.400 --> 00:28:58.239
what current branch you're on.

00:28:58.239 --> 00:29:00.079
So, that main production branch,

00:29:00.079 --> 00:29:01.760
those black dots I was showing you before,

00:29:02.319 --> 00:29:04.079
typically it's going to be called main.

00:29:04.079 --> 00:29:06.160
If you're using like an older repository,

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:07.040
an older version,

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:08.160
it may be called master.

00:29:08.719 --> 00:29:09.520
But that's typically,

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:10.319
this is the syntax

00:29:10.319 --> 00:29:11.839
for that main production branch.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:14.000
So, let's go ahead and demonstrate

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:15.760
how to create a new branch.

00:29:15.760 --> 00:29:16.880
I'm going to click on this button.

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:19.119
You're going to get a pop-up menu

00:29:19.119 --> 00:29:20.319
and I'm just going to call this

00:29:20.319 --> 00:29:23.040
test branch one, all right?

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:24.959
Don't worry too much about remote.

00:29:24.959 --> 00:29:26.319
We're not going to focus on that today.

00:29:27.599 --> 00:29:29.040
But that's pretty much all you need to do

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:30.640
is just give that branch a new name,

00:29:30.640 --> 00:29:31.280
hit create.

00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:34.319
And it's automatically going to

00:29:34.319 --> 00:29:36.239
run the git commands in the background,

00:29:36.239 --> 00:29:36.479
all right?

00:29:36.479 --> 00:29:37.599
So, that's one of the great things

00:29:37.599 --> 00:29:39.040
about the RStudio IDE

00:29:39.040 --> 00:29:40.560
and a lot of the other IDEs

00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:42.959
is that automatically takes care of that

00:29:42.959 --> 00:29:45.760
talking to git through the terminal for you.

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:49.520
Now, again, I talked about previously

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:51.920
making sure that git can talk to GitHub.

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:53.760
And this is where you're going to

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:55.359
set up those credentials, all right?

00:29:55.359 --> 00:29:56.479
It may be a little bit different

00:29:56.479 --> 00:29:57.359
in your environment,

00:29:57.359 --> 00:29:59.040
but for our demo environment,

00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:00.400
we can't save these credentials.

00:30:00.400 --> 00:30:01.760
So, I do have to enter them again.

00:30:01.760 --> 00:30:02.479
So, I'm just going to go ahead

00:30:02.479 --> 00:30:03.760
and do this really quick.

00:30:03.760 --> 00:30:05.920
I'm going to give my GitHub username.

00:30:07.439 --> 00:30:08.800
And then I'm going to supply my password.

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:09.680
Don't worry, it just won't show up

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:10.640
on the screen or anything.

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:13.680
So, go to my password manager,

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:16.479
get my GitHub token, copy it.

00:30:17.359 --> 00:30:19.199
And I'll paste it right here and hit okay.

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:22.640
You should see some logs right here

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:23.760
just letting you know everything

00:30:23.760 --> 00:30:25.439
that's going on in the background.

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:26.400
I'll hit close.

00:30:26.959 --> 00:30:28.319
And now if we look right here,

00:30:28.319 --> 00:30:31.359
you can see I'm now currently on test branch one.

00:30:31.359 --> 00:30:33.760
So, that's quickly just a very short demonstration

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:35.199
of how to create branches.

00:30:35.199 --> 00:30:37.920
And again, I just highly encourage folks

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:40.000
to explore branches more

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.239
and how they can be used in your workflows.

00:30:42.239 --> 00:30:44.079
And also just know that a lot of times

00:30:44.079 --> 00:30:46.400
like branching and merging,

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:48.479
sometimes your group may have kind of

00:30:49.199 --> 00:30:51.920
predefined practices and best practices

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:53.760
for how you want to manage branches

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:56.160
and merging those branches into production.

00:30:58.400 --> 00:30:58.880
All right.

00:30:58.880 --> 00:31:00.400
So, coming back here,

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:01.280
you've created a branch.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.560
Now I'm going to go ahead on that branch,

00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:07.040
I'm going to make a change to one of the files

00:31:07.040 --> 00:31:08.800
that we want to track from source code.

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:09.920
And we're just going to focus in

00:31:09.920 --> 00:31:10.959
on that readme file.

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:13.680
So, I'm going to make some changes

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:15.680
and I'm going to show you how you can see

00:31:15.680 --> 00:31:17.920
those changes within that Git tab.

00:31:17.920 --> 00:31:18.959
We're going to commit them

00:31:18.959 --> 00:31:20.079
and we're going to push them.

00:31:20.079 --> 00:31:20.319
All right.

00:31:20.319 --> 00:31:21.520
So, don't worry right now

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:22.560
if you don't know what those mean,

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:24.000
we're going to walk you through those steps.

00:31:25.839 --> 00:31:26.160
Okay.

00:31:26.160 --> 00:31:28.479
So, here we are within the RStudio ID,

00:31:28.479 --> 00:31:30.479
currently on that test branch one that we created.

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:33.040
And in my file directory in the bottom right,

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:34.479
you can see that readme file.

00:31:34.479 --> 00:31:36.479
Again, this was created on GitHub

00:31:36.479 --> 00:31:38.560
and I pulled it into this project.

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:39.760
So, I'm going to go ahead and click on it.

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:42.719
And here's the current state of my RStudio,

00:31:42.719 --> 00:31:43.680
of that readme file.

00:31:43.680 --> 00:31:45.520
We have the name of the repository

00:31:45.520 --> 00:31:47.359
and we see the description right here.

00:31:47.359 --> 00:31:49.359
If I come back to my repository,

00:31:49.359 --> 00:31:51.040
it's exactly what you're seeing right here.

00:31:51.760 --> 00:31:54.400
Now, let's go ahead and make a change

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:57.280
within the RStudio IDE.

00:31:57.280 --> 00:31:59.199
So, I'm going to add a new line

00:31:59.199 --> 00:32:00.880
and I'm just going to write some text saying,

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:07.680
this change was made in the RStudio IDE.

00:32:08.400 --> 00:32:12.719
And I'll give another super smiley face.

00:32:13.280 --> 00:32:13.839
Okay.

00:32:13.839 --> 00:32:14.319
That's it.

00:32:15.359 --> 00:32:16.239
Now, what I'm going to do,

00:32:17.119 --> 00:32:18.959
you'll see right here, this readme file,

00:32:18.959 --> 00:32:21.119
the name of it is in this red text.

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:22.479
That's letting you know that

00:32:22.479 --> 00:32:24.719
you currently haven't saved this file.

00:32:24.719 --> 00:32:25.439
So, when you're ready,

00:32:25.439 --> 00:32:28.319
you can click on this floppy disk icon to save it.

00:32:28.319 --> 00:32:29.119
And once you do that,

00:32:29.119 --> 00:32:30.800
I want you to keep your eyes over here

00:32:30.800 --> 00:32:32.000
on this Git window.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:32.880
So, I'm going to hit save.

00:32:34.319 --> 00:32:35.599
And as soon as I do that,

00:32:36.239 --> 00:32:39.760
Git notices that this file now has been updated.

00:32:39.760 --> 00:32:41.760
There is a change in this file

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:45.359
and Git has noticed that change.

00:32:45.359 --> 00:32:47.839
So, this readme file appears in the Git tab

00:32:47.839 --> 00:32:49.280
with this little M next to it.

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:51.439
If I hover my mouse over and just hold it there,

00:32:51.439 --> 00:32:52.239
it's going to let you know

00:32:52.239 --> 00:32:53.920
that this file has been modified.

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:56.959
So, we've made a change to this readme file.

00:32:56.959 --> 00:32:58.880
If you're happy with those changes,

00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:00.880
ultimately, what you want to do is

00:33:00.880 --> 00:33:03.920
get those changes up into the GitHub repository.

00:33:04.719 --> 00:33:06.319
Before we do that, we have to commit it.

00:33:07.119 --> 00:33:09.040
So, let's just take, again,

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:10.800
a review of where we currently are.

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:12.959
We have this readme file that has been modified

00:33:12.959 --> 00:33:15.680
and we have these two files that RStudio added

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:18.160
that are not currently being tracked.

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:21.040
So, in order to commit those changes to GitHub,

00:33:21.199 --> 00:33:23.680
we first have to do something called staging it.

00:33:23.680 --> 00:33:25.599
And I always think of it kind of like a play,

00:33:25.599 --> 00:33:26.880
like a theater, right?

00:33:26.880 --> 00:33:29.119
So, in order to, before the show goes on,

00:33:29.119 --> 00:33:32.000
you basically need to place everything onto a stage,

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:33.520
right, to prepare it for the show.

00:33:34.239 --> 00:33:35.920
So, in order to stage things

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:38.400
using the RStudio Git integrations,

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:41.280
you're going to see this column over here in these boxes.

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:43.920
So, any file you want to eventually commit

00:33:43.920 --> 00:33:46.640
and push to GitHub, we're first going to stage it.

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:49.439
So, I'm going to want to track that Git ignore.

00:33:49.439 --> 00:33:52.079
I want to track this test repo rproj file.

00:33:52.079 --> 00:33:53.839
So, you can see now it changes to A,

00:33:53.839 --> 00:33:54.800
which means it's added.

00:33:55.599 --> 00:33:58.079
And I also want to stage the readme file,

00:33:58.079 --> 00:33:59.119
those changes that we made.

00:34:00.079 --> 00:34:01.280
And once we do that,

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:02.800
we're going to click on this diff icon.

00:34:02.800 --> 00:34:04.640
And so, I actually need to stop sharing for a second

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:06.000
because I need to share my whole window

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:07.359
because we're going to get a new pop-up window.

00:34:07.359 --> 00:34:08.719
So, just give me one sec here.

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:14.879
And advanced portion of screen.

00:34:16.479 --> 00:34:16.879
Okay.

00:34:16.879 --> 00:34:18.080
So, can you give me like a thumbs up?

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:19.280
Just let me know that you can still see it.

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:19.840
Okay, perfect.

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:21.199
All right.

00:34:21.199 --> 00:34:23.439
So, I've staged all these files.

00:34:23.439 --> 00:34:26.080
Now, I'm going to click on this diff icon, right?

00:34:26.080 --> 00:34:28.560
And basically, you can click diff, you can click commit.

00:34:28.560 --> 00:34:30.320
They're going to bring up the same window.

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:31.280
So, I'm going to click diff.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.399
And diff just stands for differences, right?

00:34:34.399 --> 00:34:35.520
Shorthand for differences.

00:34:36.719 --> 00:34:38.239
Over here on the left-hand side,

00:34:38.239 --> 00:34:40.560
you can see the three files that we have staged.

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:43.040
And you can select those files.

00:34:43.040 --> 00:34:45.120
And in the main window down here in the bottom,

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:47.120
you can actually see what has been changed.

00:34:48.080 --> 00:34:51.280
Any lines that were added or any text that was added

00:34:51.280 --> 00:34:52.879
is going to show up in green.

00:34:52.879 --> 00:34:55.919
So, you can see here in the previous state of my readme file.

00:34:55.919 --> 00:34:58.159
And I've added a new line on three.

00:34:58.159 --> 00:35:00.159
And then on four, I added some text

00:35:00.159 --> 00:35:02.159
letting me know that I've made some changes to the ID.

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:04.800
And maybe what would be helpful to show

00:35:05.760 --> 00:35:08.000
is I'm actually going to make a deletion, all right?

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.399
So, let me actually delete this line right here.

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:13.040
So, you can see what that looks like.

00:35:13.040 --> 00:35:14.239
I'll hit save right here.

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:18.080
All right, let me go ahead and uncheck this and restage it.

00:35:18.639 --> 00:35:19.760
And now let me click on the diff.

00:35:20.879 --> 00:35:23.439
So, this might provide a little bit more information.

00:35:23.439 --> 00:35:25.520
So, you can see now I've deleted a line,

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:26.879
which is shown in red.

00:35:26.879 --> 00:35:30.000
And I've added two lines, a blank line and then a text line.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:31.520
So, that looks good.

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:33.040
This is a change I want to make.

00:35:33.679 --> 00:35:35.199
You can see the other files as well.

00:35:35.199 --> 00:35:36.479
Again, we're not going to worry about them.

00:35:36.479 --> 00:35:37.840
But they're all in green

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:40.479
because these are brand new files to version control.

00:35:41.520 --> 00:35:42.639
Once you're happy with this,

00:35:42.639 --> 00:35:45.520
everything is staged and ready for the show to start,

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:47.360
we can now commit it, all right?

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:48.239
And this is going to commit it

00:35:48.239 --> 00:35:50.320
to my local repository on RStudio.

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:54.000
The commit message is really an art form.

00:35:54.959 --> 00:35:58.800
This is where you need to be very explicit,

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:00.000
like kind of being intuitive.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.080
So, when you go back and read these commit messages,

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:03.280
you know what happened.

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:05.600
But you also want to keep them very short and concise.

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:08.000
You don't want to write an entire paragraph.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.040
And so, a common first commit for a project

00:36:11.040 --> 00:36:13.280
will be the init commit, right?

00:36:13.280 --> 00:36:14.080
The initial commit.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:15.600
So, that's what we're just going to do for right now.

00:36:16.399 --> 00:36:17.520
So, I'm going to go ahead.

00:36:17.520 --> 00:36:18.320
This all looks good.

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:20.239
I'm ready to commit this to version control.

00:36:20.239 --> 00:36:21.360
So, I'll hit commit.

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:25.199
It's going to run those git commands in the background

00:36:25.199 --> 00:36:26.479
using this git commit.

00:36:26.479 --> 00:36:27.439
You don't have to worry about it.

00:36:27.439 --> 00:36:28.399
It'll print some logs.

00:36:28.959 --> 00:36:30.719
If there's any error messages that occur,

00:36:30.719 --> 00:36:32.639
these log messages can be a little bit helpful

00:36:32.639 --> 00:36:33.760
to troubleshoot what's going on.

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:35.439
So, we'll close this.

00:36:36.399 --> 00:36:38.800
And now you can see my git tab is empty, right?

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:41.280
Everything is up to date locally within RStudio.

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:44.560
But you're also going to see this little information icon

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:46.159
letting you know that your branch,

00:36:46.159 --> 00:36:47.520
so this test branch one,

00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:51.439
is ahead of basically the GitHub repository by one commit.

00:36:51.439 --> 00:36:54.239
So, I've made one commit locally here within RStudio.

00:36:54.800 --> 00:36:58.000
And it's saying that, hey, you're one step ahead here.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:36:59.840
Do you want to push these up to GitHub?

00:36:59.840 --> 00:37:01.040
And that's what we're going to do next.

00:37:01.919 --> 00:37:04.399
So, right here, you're going to see these two arrows,

00:37:04.399 --> 00:37:05.360
pull and push.

00:37:06.159 --> 00:37:09.040
Let's go ahead and show you how to push changes to GitHub.

00:37:09.040 --> 00:37:10.239
It's pretty darn easy.

00:37:10.239 --> 00:37:12.800
All you have to do is push that button and it's done.

00:37:13.600 --> 00:37:17.520
Okay, you can see now it's pushed up to that GitHub repository.

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:20.000
I'm going to switch over to GitHub.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:21.919
I'm going to refresh my page here.

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:25.439
And I also need to make sure I'm on the right branch.

00:37:25.439 --> 00:37:27.199
So, you'll see currently I'm on main.

00:37:27.199 --> 00:37:31.280
But if you recall, we did all those changes to our test branch right down here.

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:34.399
So, this is the current state of that test branch

00:37:34.399 --> 00:37:35.840
on my GitHub repository.

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:37.600
You can see that gitignore is now present,

00:37:37.600 --> 00:37:39.600
that rproj file is now present.

00:37:39.600 --> 00:37:41.679
And here is my current state of my readme,

00:37:41.679 --> 00:37:42.719
which you can see down here.

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:45.120
This change was made in the RStudio IDE.

00:37:45.679 --> 00:37:48.719
So, this is how you make changes locally within RStudio

00:37:48.719 --> 00:37:50.560
and then push them up to GitHub.

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:55.439
Now, let's actually flip it in reverse.

00:37:55.439 --> 00:37:57.360
And this is actually great for collaborative work

00:37:57.360 --> 00:38:01.840
because you can have multiple people working on a single GitHub repository.

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:04.159
And maybe you come in in the morning

00:38:04.159 --> 00:38:06.879
and there's been some changes within the GitHub repository,

00:38:06.879 --> 00:38:10.399
and you want to pull in those changes before you start your work.

00:38:10.399 --> 00:38:11.679
So, that's what we're going to do next.

00:38:12.239 --> 00:38:13.040
But in order to do that,

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:17.280
we first need to make some changes to this readme on GitHub.

00:38:17.280 --> 00:38:20.159
And you can do that using this little pencil icon you see right here.

00:38:20.159 --> 00:38:21.120
So, I'm going to click on this.

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:24.959
I'm going to add two new lines.

00:38:25.760 --> 00:38:30.560
And I'm going to say this change was made in GitHub.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:34.239
Three smiley faces.

00:38:34.239 --> 00:38:35.280
And we'll hit commit change.

00:38:36.399 --> 00:38:39.199
So, it's going to be very similar to the RStudio IDE

00:38:39.199 --> 00:38:43.439
when you want to provide that kind of informative commit message.

00:38:43.439 --> 00:38:46.479
And GitHub is actually providing a pretty intuitive one.

00:38:46.479 --> 00:38:47.360
So, update readme.

00:38:47.360 --> 00:38:48.239
That sounds good.

00:38:48.239 --> 00:38:50.639
We'll commit it directly to this test branch.

00:38:52.159 --> 00:38:53.040
And there we go.

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:54.879
So, I'll come back to my repository.

00:38:56.159 --> 00:38:58.239
Now, here's the current state of my readme file.

00:38:58.239 --> 00:38:59.760
It has these two lines, right?

00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:01.520
One change was made in RStudio.

00:39:01.520 --> 00:39:02.560
One was made in GitHub.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:05.840
If I come back to my RStudio IDE,

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:07.760
I'm still on that test branch.

00:39:07.760 --> 00:39:11.199
This is the current state of my local readme file.

00:39:11.199 --> 00:39:12.959
You can see I just had this one line.

00:39:12.959 --> 00:39:16.719
So, I want to pull in those changes from that GitHub repository.

00:39:16.719 --> 00:39:18.560
And to do that, you probably guessed it.

00:39:18.560 --> 00:39:19.679
We're going to click pull.

00:39:19.679 --> 00:39:20.800
All you have to do is push it.

00:39:22.399 --> 00:39:23.919
And it's already done for me.

00:39:23.919 --> 00:39:27.840
And now you can see here is the current state of that readme file

00:39:27.840 --> 00:39:30.959
in my local environment, which matches the GitHub repository.

00:39:31.679 --> 00:39:37.600
So, that was quite a few steps that we just kind of plowed through here.

00:39:38.239 --> 00:39:39.280
We created a branch.

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:41.600
We made changes to a file, that readme file.

00:39:41.600 --> 00:39:43.040
We pushed it to GitHub.

00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:44.560
And then we pulled it from GitHub.

00:39:45.439 --> 00:39:49.679
So, now let's do something that's a little bit more data science interesting, right?

00:39:49.679 --> 00:39:54.479
We're actually going to create a piece of content, such as a Shiny application.

00:39:55.120 --> 00:39:57.120
And I'm going to show you a really cool feature

00:39:58.159 --> 00:40:00.959
to publish content to a tool called PositConnect.

00:40:01.520 --> 00:40:03.600
Again, if you don't have PositConnect, that's totally fine.

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:06.639
This is really just kind of highlighting some cool Git integrations

00:40:06.639 --> 00:40:07.919
with some of our professional tools.

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:12.159
So, let's go ahead and just create a Shiny application.

00:40:12.159 --> 00:40:14.399
So, I'm going to come back here to my RStudio IDE.

00:40:14.399 --> 00:40:16.320
I'm going to close out of this readme file.

00:40:16.959 --> 00:40:18.879
And I'm going to create a Shiny app.

00:40:18.879 --> 00:40:22.800
To do that, there's actually a built-in Shiny application to the RStudio IDE.

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:27.120
So, I can click on this dropdown in the top left and select Shiny web app.

00:40:28.479 --> 00:40:30.239
We'll just give this application a random name.

00:40:30.239 --> 00:40:32.320
I'll say NHS Shiny.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:34.000
And I'll hit Create.

00:40:35.679 --> 00:40:38.959
And now you can see in the bottom right, we have this NHS Shiny directory.

00:40:38.959 --> 00:40:42.399
If I click on it, it has a single file, app.r,

00:40:42.399 --> 00:40:45.040
which is what you're seeing over here in the top left corner.

00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:46.719
All right, so this is a Shiny application.

00:40:46.719 --> 00:40:48.080
If you're not familiar with Shiny,

00:40:48.080 --> 00:40:52.320
it's a way to create interactive web applications using only R code.

00:40:52.959 --> 00:40:54.800
All right, so it's using the Shiny package.

00:40:54.800 --> 00:40:57.760
And we can run this application locally within RStudio.

00:40:57.760 --> 00:40:58.639
So, I hit Run App.

00:40:59.520 --> 00:41:01.679
We should get this little viewer tab that opens up.

00:41:02.479 --> 00:41:06.479
And here is a running or a kind of rendered Shiny application.

00:41:06.479 --> 00:41:08.639
We have this histogram over here on the right.

00:41:08.639 --> 00:41:12.000
And I can change the number of bins by sliding this bar to the left

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:13.520
or sliding it to the right.

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:16.639
And you can see how Shiny reacts to these input changes

00:41:16.639 --> 00:41:18.080
as I slide this bar left and right.

00:41:19.040 --> 00:41:20.560
Pretty simple Shiny application,

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:24.879
but it does demonstrate the power of Shiny to explore your data interactively.

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:29.199
But let's say you want to share the Shiny application with the world.

00:41:29.919 --> 00:41:31.919
There are a few different ways to do that.

00:41:31.919 --> 00:41:35.679
But one of the ways is a tool called Posit Connect.

00:41:35.679 --> 00:41:38.159
All right, so if I come down to this little flow diagram here,

00:41:38.719 --> 00:41:42.239
you can basically take content you've created like Shiny applications

00:41:42.239 --> 00:41:45.600
and push it from RStudio and then host it on Connect

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:47.040
to make it really easy to share.

00:41:47.679 --> 00:41:52.000
There's actually a few different ways you can publish content to Connect.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:53.439
And I'm going to show you two of them.

00:41:54.879 --> 00:41:57.120
The first way, so I'm going to close this application,

00:41:59.120 --> 00:42:02.479
is to publish it directly from within the RStudio IDE.

00:42:02.479 --> 00:42:04.800
And you can do that with this little blue icon

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:06.399
you see on the top of your screen.

00:42:06.399 --> 00:42:08.239
That is our publishing button.

00:42:08.239 --> 00:42:09.439
If I was to click on this,

00:42:10.479 --> 00:42:12.719
I could choose what app I want to publish.

00:42:12.719 --> 00:42:13.760
So it's app.rfile.

00:42:13.760 --> 00:42:15.040
It's what you see over here on the left.

00:42:15.600 --> 00:42:17.760
And I can publish it to Posit Connect.

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:21.840
Now here at Posit, we call our demo environment Colorado.

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:23.199
I really have no idea why.

00:42:23.199 --> 00:42:25.199
But if I wanted to publish it to Connect,

00:42:25.199 --> 00:42:27.040
I just have to define that server,

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:29.439
give it a name, hit publish, boom, I'm done.

00:42:30.159 --> 00:42:32.239
But I want to show you a different workflow

00:42:32.239 --> 00:42:34.080
where you can take this application,

00:42:34.800 --> 00:42:36.479
host it on GitHub,

00:42:36.479 --> 00:42:41.040
and you can actually publish directly from GitHub repository.

00:42:41.040 --> 00:42:42.560
This is a really good workflow

00:42:42.560 --> 00:42:46.479
if you have multiple people working on a single application

00:42:46.479 --> 00:42:49.520
and you just want to pull in the most recent version

00:42:49.520 --> 00:42:51.600
from that GitHub repository into Connect.

00:42:52.479 --> 00:42:54.159
So to do that,

00:42:54.159 --> 00:42:56.639
we have one additional step we need to go through.

00:42:57.520 --> 00:43:00.560
And we basically need to provide Posit Connect

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:03.360
with the information about my environment,

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:05.040
like what R version am I using?

00:43:05.040 --> 00:43:06.239
So I'm using 4.2.

00:43:06.959 --> 00:43:08.560
What packages am I using?

00:43:08.560 --> 00:43:10.479
What versions of those packages?

00:43:10.479 --> 00:43:12.879
Connect needs to know a little bit more about my environment

00:43:12.879 --> 00:43:15.360
so that I can deploy this application properly.

00:43:16.159 --> 00:43:19.280
So to do that, we have to create what's known as a manifest file.

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:20.560
Now it sounds kind of scary,

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:22.399
but it's actually pretty darn easy.

00:43:22.959 --> 00:43:26.000
And that's with the help of a package called rsConnect.

00:43:27.280 --> 00:43:28.479
And inside of this package,

00:43:28.479 --> 00:43:31.120
there's a function called writeManifest.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:33.280
And the only thing you need to do

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:36.000
is provide it with the app directory.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:42.800
So my app directory is going to be this tnhs-shiny.

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:43.360
And that's it.

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:47.439
Once I hit enter, it only takes a few seconds.

00:43:47.439 --> 00:43:48.399
Keep your eyes down here.

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:51.040
And it creates this manifest.json.

00:43:51.840 --> 00:43:54.719
And again, this is all information about my environment

00:43:54.719 --> 00:43:56.000
for this application.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:57.840
So you do need to create this manifest file

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:00.879
in the same directory as the content you want to deploy.

00:44:01.439 --> 00:44:04.000
If I click on it, just to kind of show you what it looks like,

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:05.760
it's not the prettiest thing to look at,

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:07.280
but they're pretty easy to understand.

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:09.520
So you can see up here in the very top,

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:10.719
you can see some information,

00:44:10.719 --> 00:44:12.639
like what version of R am I using?

00:44:13.439 --> 00:44:16.399
What packages I'm using, such as R6.

00:44:16.719 --> 00:44:18.320
Scroll down, Rcpp.

00:44:18.879 --> 00:44:20.239
It's also going to include information,

00:44:20.239 --> 00:44:21.919
like what version of those packages.

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:24.320
So this is all just really important information

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:25.360
about my environment.

00:44:26.239 --> 00:44:27.679
If anyone on the line is familiar

00:44:27.679 --> 00:44:30.560
with another open source package called renv,

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:33.280
this is very similar to a lock file, an Rnv lock file.

00:44:33.280 --> 00:44:34.959
It just provides a little bit more information.

00:44:36.320 --> 00:44:38.080
So this is the only two things you need.

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:40.560
Your piece of content, our Shiny app right here,

00:44:40.560 --> 00:44:42.959
and you need that manifest file basically right next to it.

00:44:43.520 --> 00:44:45.040
So let's go ahead through the process

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:48.320
of taking these changes locally within RStudio

00:44:48.320 --> 00:44:50.800
and pushing it up to GitHub, all right?

00:44:50.800 --> 00:44:52.000
So you'll see in the Git tab,

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:53.520
where I now have this new directory

00:44:53.520 --> 00:44:55.439
that's not currently being tracked.

00:44:55.439 --> 00:44:58.159
